The movements of Priuce Charles Edward, after his expulsion from France on the peace of Aix-la· Chapelle were mysterious‚ but in 1750, 1752 and 1754, he is thought to have visited his adhereuts in London, and no doubt contrived to keep Oxford well informed of his designs. In the latter year occurred the famous Oxfordshire election, in which the bitterness of party spirit reached its culminating point. Writs for sum- moning Parliament were issued on April 9, being ’ retumable on May 31, and in accordance therewith, Mr. Blackass, the sheriff, held his County Court at Oxford on the 17th of April, as soon as possible aster he had received the writs. The candidates for election were Lord Wenman and Sir James Dashwood for the ‘blues’ or ‘old interest,' Lord Parker aud Sir Edward Tumer for the ‘yellows' or ‘new interest! As the candidates were strong aud had great interest, and the freeholders were numerous, it was found im- possible to determine the election upon a view; a poll was therefore demanded, and continued till April 23rd.
